revision.text:
{{italic title}} '''''Anne and Emmett''''' is a play by American [[Janet Langhart|Janet Langhart Cohen]]. It explores an imaginary conversation between [[Emmett Till]], an African American, and [[Anne Frank]], a German Jew, which takes place in ''Memory,'' a non-specific afterlife or alternate dimension. They were killed as young teenagers because of racial persecution. The play recounts the lives of the Till and Frank, comparing and contrasting the events in their lives and deaths.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.anneandemmett.com/play/synopsis |title=Synopsis &#124; Anne & Emmett |publisher=Anneandemmett.com |date= |accessdate=2011-07-28| archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20110707144435/http://anneandemmett.com/play/synopsis| archivedate= 7 July 2011 <!--DASHBot-->| deadurl= no}}</ref>
The show features recorded narration by [[Morgan Freeman]], and a score by [[Joshua Coyne]].<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/wp-dyn/content/article/2009/06/13/AR2009061302113.html |title=Courtland Milloy on the Debut of 'Anne and Emmett' |author=Courtland Milloy |publisher=Washingtonpost.com |date= 2009-06-14|accessdate=2011-07-28}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|last=Furchtgott |first=Diana |url=http://www.sfexaminer.com/opinion/op-eds/2011/06/education-policies-fail-brilliant-young-multi-instrumentalist |title=Education policies fail brilliant young multi-instrumentalist &#124; Diana Furchtgott-Roth &#124; Op Eds &#124; San Francisco Examiner |publisher=Sfexaminer.com |date= |accessdate=2011-07-28 |deadurl=yes |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120605033012/http://www.sfexaminer.com/opinion/op-eds/2011/06/education-policies-fail-brilliant-young-multi-instrumentalist |archivedate=2012-06-05 }}</ref>
==Shooting== The play was set to premiere at the [[United States Holocaust Memorial Museum]] on June 10, 2009, as part of the commemoration of Anne Frank's 80th birthday.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://content.usatoday.com/communities/religion/post/2009/06/67585427/1 |title=Fate of Anne Frank, Emmett Till plays out in our minds - Faith & Reason - USATODAY.com |publisher=Content.usatoday.com |date=2009-06-03 |accessdate=2011-07-28}}</ref> The premiere was cancelled due to a [[United States Holocaust Memorial Museum shooting|shooting]] at the museum, which resulted in the death of a museum guard.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://washingtonjewishweek.com/main.asp?SectionID=4&subsectionID=4&articleID=10982 |title=Shooting brings poignancy to ''Anne and Emmett'' play |work=Washington Jewish Week |date=2009-09-02 |accessdate=2011-07-28 |deadurl=yes |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20111006024652/http://washingtonjewishweek.com/main.asp?SectionID=4&subsectionID=4&articleID=10982 |archivedate=2011-10-06 }}</ref><ref>{{cite web|author=Tell Me More |url=https://www.npr.org/templates/story/story.php?storyId=105291623 |title=Museum Shooting Draws Attention To Play About Hate |publisher=NPR |date=2009-06-12 |accessdate=2011-07-28}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|last=Stabley |first=Matthew |url=http://www.nbcwashington.com/news/local/One-Shot-at-Holocaust-Museum.html |title=Slain Museum Guard's Kindness Repaid With Bullet |publisher=NBC Washington |date= |accessdate=2011-07-28}}</ref>
==Use in training police== The [[New York City Police Department]] has had the play produced for audiences of its police officers, using it to teach tolerance.<ref>{http://newyork.cbslocal.com/2015/10/16/nypd-anne-emmett-tolerance-play/ | NYPD Begins Using One-Act Play ‘Anne & Emmett’ To Teach Tolerance}</ref>
