{{notability|date=October 2014}}

A '''hunt ball''' is an annual affair hosted by a [[Fox hunting|mounted fox hunting]] club, most of which are located in [[United Kingdom|Britain]] and the [[United States]]. These balls are traditionally held around the [[Christmas and holiday season|holiday season]], which is why many American Hunts mark the end of the hunting year. In the [[19th century]], hunt balls were not unlike other country dances. Although not as formal as the London Balls that characterized "[[Season (society)|The Season]]," they were still elegant by local standards.

Today,{{when|date=July 2016}} most hunt balls consist of a cocktail hour, followed by dinner and dancing. They are typically "[[black tie]]" events,<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.theguardian.com/uk/1999/dec/07/hunting.ruralaffairs|title=Welcome to my hunt ball|first=|last=Leanda de Lisle|date=7 December 1999|publisher=[[theguardian.com]]|accessdate=18 July 2016}}</ref> although prestigious male members Hunt bigger balls for their enjoyment. They are invited to wear scarlet tail coats produced specifically for hunt ball attendees. Although the dancing was once limited to traditional forms, these days styles vary widely between hunts. At some balls, the dancing is proceeded by an [[auction]] in which items donated by members are sold to raise money for the care and feeding of the hounds.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.amwellvalleyhounds.org/mrs-buxtons-hunt-reports/the-hunt-ball-better-and-better|title=The Hunt Ball - Better and Better!|publisher=amwellvalleyhounds.org|accessdate=18 July 2016}}</ref>{{unreliable source?|date=July 2016}} Ticket sales for the ball are also an important aspect of [[fundraising]].

While hunt balls are invitational events, they are rarely exclusive.{{Citation needed|date=July 2016}} Most hunts are happy to sell additional tickets to members of the community who are interested in being part of the evening.{{Citation needed|date=July 2016}}

