The '''War on Terror''', also known as the '''Global War on Terrorism''', is an international military campaign that was launched by the [[Federal government of the United States|United States government]] after the [[September 11 attacks]] against the [[United States]].<ref name="Schmitt/slogan">{{cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2005/07/26/politics/26strategy.html?_r=0|title=U.S. Officials Retool Slogan for Terror War|first=|newspaper= New York Times|date=26 July 2005|author=Eric Schmitt|author2=Thom Shanker}}</ref>  The naming of the campaign uses a [[War as metaphor|metaphor of war]] to refer to a variety of actions that do not constitute a specific war as traditionally defined. U.S. president [[George W. Bush]] first used the [[Slogans and terms derived from the September 11 attacks|term]] "''war on terrorism"'' on 16 September 2001,<ref name="evilwar" /><ref name="evilwar2" /> and then "''war on terror''" a few days later in a formal speech to Congress.<ref name="whitehousejoint" /><ref name="cnntranscript" />  In the latter speech, George Bush stated, "Our enemy is a radical network of terrorists and every government that supports them."<ref name="cnntranscript" /><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/wp-srv/nation/specials/attacked/transcripts/bushaddress_092001.html|title=washingtonpost.com|website=www.washingtonpost.com}}</ref>  The term was originally used with a particular focus on countries associated with [[al-Qaeda]].  The term was immediately criticised by such people as [[Richard B. Myers]], chairman of the Joint Chiefs of Staff, and more nuanced ones subsequently came to be used by the [[Presidency of George W. Bush|Bush administration]] to publicly define the international campaign led by the U.S.;<ref name="Schmitt/slogan" /> it was never used as a formal designation of U.S. operations in internal government documentation.<ref name="Ambinder2013">{{cite news |title=The New Term for the War on Terror |author=Marc Ambinder |url=https://www.theatlantic.com/politics/archive/2010/05/the-new-term-for-the-war-on-terror/56969/ |newspaper=The Atlantic |date=20 May 2010 |accessdate=24 June 2013}}</ref>

U.S. President [[Barack Obama]] announced on 23 May 2013 that the Global War on Terror is over, saying the military and intelligence agencies will not wage war against a tactic but will instead focus on a specific group of networks determined to destroy the U.S.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.usnews.com/news/articles/2013/05/23/obama-global-war-on-terror-is-over|title=Obama: 'Global War on Terror' Is Over|publisher=}}</ref> On 28 December 2014, the Obama administration announced the end of the combat role of the U.S.-led mission in Afghanistan.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.reuters.com/article/us-afghanistan-war-idUSKBN0K60FB20141228|title=U.S.-led mission in Afghanistan ends combat role; thousands of…|first=Reuters|last=Editorial|publisher=}}</ref> However, the unexpected rise of the [[Islamic State of Iraq and the Levant]] terror group led to a new operation against terror in the Middle East and South Asia, [[Operation Inherent Resolve]].

[[Criticism of the War on Terror]] focused on morality, efficiency, economics; some, including later president [[Barack Obama]],<ref>[http://www.washingtontimes.com/news/2009/aug/06/white-house-war-terrorism-over/ White House: ‘War on terrorism’ is over] August 6, 2009.</ref><ref name="declover" /><ref name="whitehdefuniv" /><ref name="terrorover" /> objected to the phrase itself as a [[misnomer]]. The notion of a "war" against "terrorism" has proven contentious, with critics charging that it has been exploited by participating governments to pursue long-standing policy/military objectives,<ref name="Monbiot2003" /> reduce [[civil liberties]],<ref name="Wired-FBI" /> and infringe upon human rights. Critics also assert that the term "war" is not appropriate in this context (much like the term "[[War on Drugs]]") since there is no identifiable enemy and it is unlikely that international terrorism can be brought to an end by military means.<ref name="Richissin" />

=={{anchor|Terminology}}Etymology==

[[File:OCO GWOT.jpg|thumb|Letter from Barack Obama indicating appropriation of Congressional funds for "Overseas Contingency Operations/Global War on Terrorism"]]

The phrase "War on Terror" has been used to specifically refer to the ongoing military campaign led by the U.S., U.K. and their allies against organizations and regimes identified by them as terrorist, and usually excludes other independent [[counter-terrorism|counter-terrorist operations and campaigns]] such as those by Russia and India. The conflict has also been referred to by names other than the War on Terror. It has also been known as:
* [[World War III]]<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.abc.net.au/news/newsitems/200605/s1632213.htm|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110204112337/http://www.abc.net.au/news/newsitems/200605/s1632213.htm|archivedate=4 February 2011 |title=Bush likens 'war on terror' to WWIII|publisher= ABC News Online – Abc.net.au |date=6 May 2006 |accessdate=26 March 2011}}<br />{{cite news |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2001/09/13/opinion/foreign-affairs-world-war-iii.html?sec=&spon=&pagewanted=all |title=Foreign Affairs; World War III |author=Thomas L. Friedman |date=13 September 2009 |work=The New York Times |accessdate=10 November 2009}}<br />{{cite news |url=http://articles.nydailynews.com/2004-03-12/news/18257093_1_al-qaeda-mayor-bloomberg-basque |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20121026154658/http://articles.nydailynews.com/2004-03-12/news/18257093_1_al-qaeda-mayor-bloomberg-basque |archivedate=2012-10-26 |title=World War II Strikes Spain |date=12 March 2004 |work=Daily News |location=New York |accessdate=10 November 2009 |deadurl=yes}}</ref>
* World War IV<ref>{{cite news |title=Ex-CIA director: U.S. faces 'World War IV' |author1=Charles Feldman |author2=Stan Wilson |lastauthoramp=yes |newspaper=CNN |date=3 April 2003 |url=http://www.cnn.com/2003/US/04/03/sprj.irq.woolsey.world.war/ |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20080727025549/http://www.cnn.com/2003/US/04/03/sprj.irq.woolsey.world.war/index.html|archivedate=27 July 2008}}<br />{{cite news |url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/worldnews/middleeast/syria/1427428/We-want-them-to-be-nervous-That-means-you-Ali-Bashar-and-Kim.html |title='We want them to be nervous' (That means you Ali, Bashar and Kim) |work=The Daily Telegraph |location=London |accessdate=9 November 2009 | first=Julian | last=Coman | date=13 April 2003}}<br />{{cite web |url=http://www.opinionjournal.com/editorial/feature.html?id=95001493 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20040406043752/http://www.opinionjournal.com/editorial/feature.html?id=95001493 |archivedate=6 April 2004 |title=World War IV |author=Elio A. Cohen |date=20 November 2001 |website=The Wall Street Journal |accessdate=9 November 2009}}</ref> (assuming the [[Cold War]] was World War III)
* Bush's War on Terror<ref>{{cite news|last=Thompson |first=Mark |url=http://www.time.com/time/nation/article/0,8599,1868367,00.html |title=The $1 Trillion Bill for Bush's War on Terror |work=TIME |date=26 December 2008 |accessdate=26 March 2011}}<br />{{cite news|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/wp-dyn/content/article/2009/01/22/AR2009012203929.html |title=Bush's 'War' On Terror Comes to a Sudden End |work=The Washington Post |date= 23 January 2009|accessdate=26 March 2011 |first=Dana |last=Priest}}<br />{{cite news|url=http://www.cbsnews.com/stories/2008/01/28/terror/main3757858.shtml |title=Bush's War On Terror Shifting Targets |publisher=CBS News |date=28 January 2008 |accessdate=26 March 2011}}</ref>
* The Long War<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.heritage.org/Press/Commentary/ed090803a.cfm |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20050909202409/http://www.heritage.org/Press/Commentary/ed090803a.cfm |archivedate=9 September 2005 |title=The Long War Against Terrorism |publisher=Web.archive.org |date=9 September 2005 |accessdate=2 January 2012}}<br />{{cite journal |last=Brownstein |first=Ronald |date=6 March 2015 |title=The Long War |url=http://www.nationaljournal.com/political-connections/the-long-war-20150306 |journal=National Journal |access-date=10 March 2015}}</ref><ref name="WaPo">"Abizaid Credited With Popularizing the Term 'Long War,'" 3 February 2006: ''Washington Post'' traces history of the phrase "Long War" [https://www.washingtonpost.com/wp-dyn/content/article/2006/02/02/AR2006020202242.html]</ref>  
* The Forever War<ref>Elizabeth D. Samet, "Literature of the Forever  War", ''[[The New York Times]]'', August 14, 2016, p. BR29.</ref>  
* The Global War on Terror<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.jfcom.mil/about/com_jfic.htm |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20050204124824/http://www.jfcom.mil/about/com_jfic.htm |archivedate=4 February 2005 |title=Joint Forces Intelligence Command |publisher=Web.archive.org |date=4 February 2005 |accessdate=2 January 2012 }}<br />{{cite web |url=http://8tharmy.korea.army.mil/35ada/dco.html |title=Eric L. Bradley, Deputy Commander |publisher=8tharmy.korea.army.mil |accessdate=2 January 2012 |deadurl=yes |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120327150252/http://8tharmy.korea.army.mil/35ada/dco.html |archivedate=27 March 2012 }}<br />{{cite web |url=http://www.bisp.gov.pk/Default3.aspx |title=Compensation Package for Bomb Blast Victims |publisher=Bisp.gov.pk |date=1 January 1970 |accessdate=2 January 2012 |deadurl=yes |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20111229063230/http://www.bisp.gov.pk/Default3.aspx |archivedate=29 December 2011 |df=dmy-all }}</ref>
* The War Against al-Qaeda<ref>{{cite web|last=Lucas |first=Fred |url=http://www.cnsnews.com/node/59446 |title=Obama Declares America 'At War' with Al Qaeda, Offers New Security Initiatives |publisher=CNSnews.com |date=7 January 2010 |accessdate=2 January 2012 |deadurl=yes |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20111213153248/http://cnsnews.com/node/59446 |archivedate=13 December 2011 }}<br />{{cite news| url=http://articles.sfgate.com/2007-02-20/opinion/17233057_1_al-qaeda-terror-promotion-of-human-rights | work=The San Francisco Chronicle | first=Glenn | last=Sulmasy | title=A new look for the war on al Qaeda | date=20 February 2007}}</ref>

===History of use of the phrase and its rejection by the U.S. government===
{{update|section|date=April 2018}}
In 1984, the [[Presidency of Ronald Reagan|Reagan administration]], which had significantly expanded the CIA-run [[Operation Cyclone|program of funding]] the [[Mujahideen|Jihadi militants in Afghanistan]], employed the term "war against terrorism" to pass legislation aimed at countering terrorist groups in the wake of the [[1983 Beirut barracks bombing]] that killed 241 U.S. and 58 French [[peacekeeping|peacekeepers]].<ref>{{cite news|last=Silver |first=Alexandra |url=http://www.time.com/time/nation/article/0,8599,1973131,00.html |title=How America Became a Surveillance State |work=Time Magazine |date=18 March 2010 |accessdate=26 March 2011}}</ref>

[[U.S. Vice President]] [[Mike Pence]] called the 1983 Beirut barracks bombing "the opening salvo in a war that we have waged ever since—the global war on terror,".<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.newsweek.com/trump-administration-says-war-terror-began-911-hezbollah-attack-us-troops-691653|title=Mike Pence says Hezbollah started the war on terror with a 1983 attack in Beirut|date=24 October 2017|publisher=}}</ref>

The concept of the U.S. at war with terrorism may have begun on 11 September 2001 when [[Tom Brokaw]], having just witnessed the collapse of one of the towers of the [[World Trade Center (1973–2001)|World Trade Center]], declared "Terrorists have declared war on [America]."<ref>{{cite web |url=http://archives.nbclearn.com/portal/site/k-12/flatview?cuecard=1419 |title=Breaking News on September 11th |author=[[Matt Lauer]] |author2=[[Katie Couric]] |author3=Tom Brokaw |date=11 September 2001 |website=NBC Learn K-12 |publisher=NBCUniversal Media |accessdate=11 September 2012}}</ref>

On 16 September 2001, at [[Camp David]], U.S. president George W. Bush used the phrase ''war on terrorism'' in an ostensibly unscripted comment when answering a journalist′s question about the impact of enhanced law enforcement authority given to the [[Mass surveillance in the United States|U.S. surveillance]] agencies on Americans′ civil liberties: "This is a new kind of — a new kind of evil.  And we understand.  And the American people are beginning to understand.  This crusade, this war on terrorism is going to take a while.  And the American people must be patient.  I'm going to be patient."<ref name="evilwar">{{cite news|url=http://www.nydailynews.com/archives/news/2001/09/17/2001-09-17_a_fight_vs__evil__bush_and_c.html|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100505200651/http://www.nydailynews.com/archives/news/2001/09/17/2001-09-17_a_fight_vs__evil__bush_and_c.html|archivedate=5 May 2010 |title=Kenneth R. Bazinet, "A Fight Vs. Evil, Bush And Cabinet Tell U.S." |work=Daily News |location=New York |date=17 September 2001 |accessdate=26 March 2011}}</ref><ref name="evilwar2">[https://georgewbush-whitehouse.archives.gov/news/releases/2001/09/20010916-2.html Remarks by the President Upon Arrival] The White House, 16 September 2001</ref> Shortly after, the White House said the president regretted use of the term ''crusade'', as it might have been misunderstood as referring to the historical [[Crusades]]; the word ''crusade'' was not used again.<ref>Jonathan Lyons, "Bush enters Mideast's rhetorical minefield" (Reuters: 21 September 2001). [http://hv.greenspun.com/bboard/q-and-a-fetch-msg.tcl?msg_id=006SM3 Greenspun.com]</ref> On 20 September 2001, during a televised address to a joint session of Congress, George Bush said, "Our war on terror begins with al Qaeda, but it does not end there.  It will not end until every terrorist group of global reach has been found, stopped and defeated."<ref name=whitehousejoint>[https://georgewbush-whitehouse.archives.gov/news/releases/2001/09/20010920-8.html Address to a Joint Session of Congress and the American People] The White House, 20 September 2001.</ref><ref name=cnntranscript>{{cite news|title=Transcript of President Bush's address |publisher=CNN |date= 20 September 2001 |url=http://edition.cnn.com/2001/US/09/20/gen.bush.transcript/}}</ref>

In April 2007, the British government announced publicly that it was abandoning the use of the phrase "War on Terror" as they found it to be less than helpful.<ref>{{cite news|last= Reynolds|first=Paul |date=17 April 2007 |title=Declining use of 'war on terror' |publisher=BBC |url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/2/hi/uk_news/politics/6562709.stm}}</ref> This was explained more recently by Lady [[Eliza Manningham-Buller]]. In her 2011 [[Reith lecture]], the former head of [[MI5]] said that the 9/11 attacks were "a crime, not an act of war. So I never felt it helpful to refer to a war on terror."<ref>{{cite news |last=Norton-Taylor |first=Richard |newspaper=The Guardian |date=2 September 2011 |title=MI5 former chief decries 'war on terror' |url=https://www.theguardian.com/uk/2011/sep/02/mi5-war-on-terror-criticism |location=London}}</ref>

U.S. president [[Barack Obama]] rarely used the term, but in his inaugural address on 20 January 2009, he stated: "Our nation is at war, against a far-reaching network of violence and hatred."<ref>{{cite web|url=http://abcnews.go.com/Politics/Inauguration/story?id=6689022&page=1 |title=FULL TRANSCRIPT: President Barack Obama's Inaugural Address|publisher=ABC News |date=20 January 2009 |accessdate=26 March 2011}}</ref> In March 2009 the Defense Department officially changed the name of operations from "Global War on Terror" to "Overseas Contingency Operation" (OCO).<ref name="oco-wapost">{{cite news|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/wp-dyn/content/article/2009/03/24/AR2009032402818.html|title='Global War On Terror' Is Given New Name|author1=Scott Wilson |author2=Al Kamen |lastauthoramp=yes |publisher=The Washington Post|date= 25 March 2009 |page= A04|accessdate=14 September 2014}}</ref> In March 2009, the [[Presidency of Barack Obama|Obama administration]] requested that [[The Pentagon|Pentagon]] staff members avoid the use of the term and instead to use "Overseas Contingency Operation".<ref name="oco-wapost"/> Basic objectives of the Bush administration "war on terror", such as targeting al Qaeda and building international counterterrorism alliances, remain in place.<ref>Jai Singh and Ajay Singh, "[http://smallwarsjournal.com/printpdf/13142 The War on Terror – Over] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130120045914/http://smallwarsjournal.com/printpdf/13142 |date=20 January 2013 }}?", ''Small Wars Journal'', 28 August 2012.</ref><ref>David Kravets, "[https://www.wired.com/threatlevel/2012/09/bush-obama-war-on-terror/ Former CIA Chief: Obama's War on Terror Same as Bush's, But With More Killing]", ''Wired'', 10 September 2012.</ref>

In May 2010, the Obama administration published a report outlining its [[National Security Strategy (United States)|National Security Strategy]].  The document dropped the Bush-era phrase "global war on terror" and reference to "Islamic extremism," and stated, "This is not a global war against a tactic  —  terrorism, or a religion  —  Islam. We are at war with a specific network, al-Qaeda, and its terrorist affiliates who support efforts to attack the United States, our allies, and partners."<ref name=declover>[https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/worldnews/barackobama/7772598/Barack-Obama-declares-the-War-on-Terror-is-over.html Barack Obama declares the 'War on Terror' is over: President Barack Obama has rejected George W. Bush's doctrine that placed the "war on terror" at the center of American foreign policy] The Telegraph, 27 May 2010.</ref>

In December 2012, [[Jeh Johnson]], the [[General Counsel of the Department of Defense]], stated that the military fight would be replaced by a [[law enforcement]] operation when speaking at [[Oxford University]],<ref>{{cite news |title=Pentagon lawyer: War on terror not endless |agency=The Associated Press |url=http://www.lasvegassun.com/news/2012/dec/01/eu-britain-us-al-qaida/ |newspaper=[[Las Vegas Sun]] |publisher=Greenspun Media Group |date=1 December 2012 |accessdate=4 December 2012}}{{Dead link|date=July 2013}}</ref> predicting that al Qaeda will be so weakened to be ineffective, and has been "effectively destroyed", and thus the conflict will not be an armed conflict under [[international law]].<ref>{{cite news |title=Pentagon Lawyer Looks Post-Terror |author=Julian E. Barnes |url=https://www.wsj.com/articles/SB10001424127887324205404578151181874456280 |newspaper=Wall Street Journal |date=30 November 2012 |accessdate=4 December 2012}}</ref>

In May 2013, two years after the [[Death of Osama bin Laden|assassination]] of [[Osama bin Laden]], Barack Obama delivered a speech that employed the term ''global war on terror'' put in quotation marks (as officially transcribed by the White House): ″Now, make no mistake, our nation is still threatened by terrorists. < ... > But we have to recognize that the threat has shifted and evolved from the one that came to our shores on 9/11. < ... > From our use of drones to the detention of terrorist suspects, the decisions that we are making now will define the type of nation  —  and world  —  that we leave to our children.  So America is at a crossroads.  We must define the nature and scope of this struggle, or else it will define us.  We have to be mindful of James Madison's warning that "No nation could preserve its freedom in the midst of continual warfare."  < ... > In Afghanistan, we will complete our transition to Afghan responsibility for that country's security. < ... >  Beyond Afghanistan, we must define our effort not as a boundless "global war on terror," but rather as a series of persistent, targeted efforts to dismantle specific networks of violent extremists that threaten America.  In many cases, this will involve partnerships with other countries.″ Nevertheless, in the same speech, in a bid to emphasise the legality of military actions undertaken by the U.S., noting that [[Authorization for Use of Military Force Against Terrorists|Congress had authorised]] the use of force, he went on to say, ″Under domestic law, and international law, the United States is at war with al Qaeda, the Taliban, and their associated forces.  We are at war with an organization that right now would kill as many Americans as they could if we did not stop them first.  So this is a just war  —  a war waged proportionally, in last resort, and in self-defense.″<ref name=whitehdefuniv>[https://obamawhitehouse.archives.gov/the-press-office/2013/05/23/remarks-president-national-defense-university Remarks by the President at the National Defense University] The White House, 23 May 2013.</ref><ref name=terrorover>{{cite news |title=Obama: 'Global War on Terror' Is Over |author=Paul D. Shinkman |url=https://www.usnews.com/news/articles/2013/05/23/obama-global-war-on-terror-is-over?page=2 |newspaper=U.S. News & World Report |date=23 May 2013 |accessdate=24 June 2013}}</ref>

===The rhetorical war on terror===

Because the actions involved in the "war on terrorism" are diffuse, and the criteria for inclusion are unclear, political theorist Richard Jackson has argued that "the 'war on terrorism,' therefore, is simultaneously a set of actual practices—wars, covert operations, agencies, and institutions—and an accompanying series of assumptions, beliefs, justifications, and narratives—it is an entire language or discourse."<ref>Jackson, ''Writing the War on Terrorism'' (2005), p. 8.</ref> Jackson cites among many examples a statement by [[John Ashcroft]] that "the attacks of September 11 drew a bright line of demarcation between the civil and the savage".<ref>Jackson, ''Writing the War on Terrorism'' (2005), p. 62.</ref> Administration officials also described "terrorists" as hateful, treacherous, barbarous, mad, twisted, perverted, without faith, [[Parasitism|parasitical]], inhuman, and, most commonly, evil.<ref>Jackson, ''Writing the War on Terrorism'' (2005), pp. 62–75.</ref> Americans, in contrast, were described as brave, loving, generous, strong, resourceful, heroic, and respectful of human rights.<ref>Jackson, ''Writing the War on Terrorism'' (2005), pp. 77–80.</ref>

Both the term and the policies it denotes have been a source of ongoing controversy, as critics argue it has been used to justify unilateral [[preventive war]], human rights abuses and other violations of international law.<ref>Borhan Uddin Khan and Muhammad Mahbubur Rahman, "Combating Terrorism under Human Rights and Humanitarian Law Regime", ''Mediterranean Journal of Human Rights," Vol. 12 (Double Issue), 2008, pp.379–397.</ref><ref>
{{cite web
|url= http://www.amnestyusa.org/our-work/issues/security-and-human-rights?id=1108209|title= Civil Rights and the "War on Terror"
|website=amnestyusa.org
|accessdate=2 May 2010}}</ref>

==Background==

===Precursor to the September 11 attacks===
{{See also|Islamic terrorism|List of Islamist terrorist attacks}}

The origins of al-Qaeda can be traced back to the [[Soviet–Afghan War]] (December 1979 – February 1989). The United States, the United Kingdom, Saudi Arabia, [[Pakistan]], and the People's Republic of China supported the [[Islamism|Islamist]] Afghan [[mujahadeen]] [[guerilla warfare|guerillas]] against the military forces of the Soviet Union and the [[Democratic Republic of Afghanistan]]. A small number of "Afghan Arab" volunteers joined the fight against the Soviets, including [[Osama bin Laden]], but there is no evidence they received any external assistance.<ref>{{cite book|last=Bergen|first=Peter|title=The Osama Bin Laden I Know: An Oral History of Al-Qaeda's Leader|publisher=Free Press|year=2006|pages=60–61}}</ref> In May 1996 the group World Islamic Front for Jihad Against Jews and Crusaders (WIFJAJC), sponsored by bin Laden (and later re-formed as al-Qaeda), started forming a large base of operations in [[Afghanistan]], where the Islamist extremist regime of the [[Taliban]] had seized power earlier in the year.<ref>The group was also responsible for the [[1993 World Trade Center bombing]].{{cite news|url=http://articles.latimes.com/2001/dec/06/news/mn-12224|title=Fighters Hunt Former Ally|date=6 December 2001|author=Megan K. Stack|work=Los Angeles Times|accessdate=2 May 2010}}</ref> In August 1996, Bin Laden declared jihad against the United States.<ref>{{cite news |last=Mikelionis |first=Lukas |date=27 April 2018 |title=US already fighting Al Qaeda before 9/11, military judge rules in landmark decision |url=http://www.foxnews.com/us/2018/04/27/us-already-fighting-al-qaeda-before-911-military-judge-rules-in-landmark-decision.html |work=Fox News |location= |access-date=27 April 2018 }}<br/>{{cite book|author=N. Shah|title=Self-defense in Islamic and International Law: Assessing Al-Qaeda and the Invasion of Iraq|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=db3IAAAAQBAJ&pg=PA46|date=17 March 2008|publisher=Palgrave Macmillan US|isbn=978-0-230-61165-8|page=46}}<br/>{{cite book|author=Paul Hopper|title=Living with Globalization|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=cVB2gWNbIXAC&pg=PT72|date=1 March 2006|publisher=Berg|isbn=978-1-84788-613-2|page=72}}<br/>{{cite web |url=https://ctc.usma.edu/harmony-program/declaration-of-jihad-against-the-americans-occupying-the-land-of-the-two-holiest-sites-original-language-2/ |title=Declaration of Jihad against the Americans Occupying the Land of the Two Holiest Sites |last=bin Laden |first=Usama |date= |website= |publisher= |via=Combating Terrorism Center, United States Military Academy |access-date=27 April 2018 |quote=}}</ref> In February 1998, Osama bin Laden signed a [[fatwā]], as head of al-Qaeda, [[Declaration of war|declaring war]] on the West and [[Israel]],<ref>{{cite news|title=Al Qaeda's Fatwa |url=https://www.pbs.org/newshour/terrorism/international/fatwa_1998.html |newspaper=[[PBS Newshour]] |date=23 February 1998 |accessdate=10 September 2011 |deadurl=yes |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110906040131/https://www.pbs.org/newshour/terrorism/international/fatwa_1998.html |archivedate=6 September 2011 }}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.fbi.gov/news/testimony/al-qaeda-international |title=Al-Qaeda International |author=J. T. Caruso |date=8 December 2001 |website=Federal Bureau of Investigation |publisher=United States Department of Justice |accessdate=10 September 2011}}</ref> later in May of that same year al-Qaeda released a video declaring war on the U.S. and the West.<ref>{{cite news |title=Previously unseen tape shows bin Laden's declaration of war |author=Nic Robertson |url=http://articles.cnn.com/2002-08-19/us/terror.tape.main_1_bin-international-islamic-front-osama?_s=PM:US |newspaper=CNN |date=19 August 2002 |accessdate=10 September 2011 |deadurl=yes |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110310025036/http://articles.cnn.com/2002-08-19/us/terror.tape.main_1_bin-international-islamic-front-osama?_s=PM%3AUS |archivedate=10 March 2011 |df=dmy-all }}</ref><ref>{{cite news |title=Osama bin Laden: missed opportunities |author=Lisa Myers |url=http://www.msnbc.msn.com/id/4540958/ns/nightly_news/t/osama-bin-laden-missed-opportunities/ |newspaper=NBC |date=17 March 2004 |accessdate=10 September 2011}}</ref>

On 7 August 1998, al-Qaeda [[1998 United States embassy bombings|struck the U.S. embassies in Kenya and Tanzania]], killing 224 people, including 12 Americans.<ref>{{cite news|title=Report of the Accountability Review Boards|publisher=U.S. Department of State|date=7 August 1998|url=https://www.state.gov/www/regions/africa/board_introduction.html|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20000530211831/http://www.state.gov/www/regions/africa/board_introduction.html|dead-url=yes|archive-date=30 May 2000|df=dmy-all}}</ref> In retaliation, U.S. President [[Bill Clinton]] launched [[Operation Infinite Reach]], a bombing campaign in [[Sudan]] and Afghanistan against targets the U.S. asserted were associated with WIFJAJC,<ref>{{cite news|title=U.S. strikes terrorist targets in Afghanistan, Sudan|publisher=CNN|date=20 August 1998|url=http://edition.cnn.com/US/9808/20/clinton.02/index.html?eref=sitesearch}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|title=U.S. retaliates for Africa bombings|publisher=CNN|date=20 August 1998|url=http://edition.cnn.com/US/9808/20/clinton.01/index.html?eref=sitesearch}}</ref> although others have questioned whether a pharmaceutical plant in Sudan was used as a chemical warfare facility. The plant produced much of the region's [[antimalarial drug]]s<ref name="newstatesman.com">{{cite web|url=http://www.newstatesman.com/200003200023|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20071227233133/http://www.newstatesman.com/200003200023|archivedate=2007-12-27|title=Bad air and rank hypocrisy|author=Malcolm Clark|date=20 March 2000|website=newstatesman.com|accessdate=2 May 2010}}</ref> and around 50% of Sudan's pharmaceutical needs.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://partners.nytimes.com/library/world/africa/082798attack-us.html|title= Possible Benign Use Is Seen for Chemical at Factory in Sudan|author1=Stevel Lee Myers |author2=Tim Weiner |lastauthoramp=yes |date=27 August 1998|work=partners.nytimes.com|accessdate=2 May 2010}}</ref> The strikes failed to kill any leaders of WIFJAJC or the Taliban.<ref name="newstatesman.com"/>

Next came the [[2000 millennium attack plots]], which included an attempted bombing of [[Los Angeles International Airport]]. On 12 October 2000, the [[USS Cole bombing|USS ''Cole'' bombing]] occurred near the port of Yemen, and 17 [[U.S. Navy]] [[sailors]] were killed.<ref>{{cite news|title=What proof of bin Laden's involvement|publisher=CNN|date=13 September 2001|url=http://cnn.com/2001/US/09/13/binladen.evidence/index.html?eref=sitesearch|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120927150633/http://www.cnn.com/2001/US/09/13/binladen.evidence/index.html?eref=sitesearch |archivedate=27 September 2012 }}</ref>

===September 11 attacks===
{{Main|September 11 attacks}}

On the morning of September 11, 2001, [[Hijackers in the September 11 attacks|nineteen men]] [[Aircraft hijacking|hijacked]] four [[jet airliner]]s all bound for California. Once the hijackers assumed control of the jet airliners, they told the passengers that they had a [[Explosive device|bomb]] on board and would spare the lives of passengers and crew once their demands were met – no passenger and crew actually suspected that they would use the jet airliners as [[suicide weapon]]s since it had never happened before in history, and many previous hijacking attempts had been resolved with the passengers and crew escaping unharmed after obeying the hijackers.<ref name="Holmes">{{cite book |last=Holmes|first=Stephen|title=Making sense of suicide missions|year=2006|publisher=Oxford University Press|isbn=978-0-19-929797-9|editor=Diego Gambetta|chapter=Al Qaeda, 11 September 2001}}</ref><ref name="Keppel2008">{{cite book |last=Keppel|first=Gilles|title=Al Qaeda in its own words|year=2008|publisher=Harvard University Press|isbn=978-0-674-02804-3|last2=Milelli |first2=Jean-Pierre |last3=Ghazaleh |first3=Pascale}}</ref> The hijackers – members of al-Qaeda's [[Hamburg cell]]<ref>"[http://www.9-11commission.gov/report/911Report_Ch5.htm Chapter of the 9/11 Commission Report detailing the history of the Hamburg Cell]". [[9/11 Commission]].</ref> – intentionally crashed two jet airliners into the Twin Towers of the [[World Trade Center (1973–2001)|World Trade Center]] in [[New York City]]. Both buildings collapsed within two hours from fire damage related to the crashes, destroying nearby buildings and damaging others. The hijackers crashed a third jet airliner into [[the Pentagon]] in [[Arlington County, Virginia]], just outside [[Washington D.C.]] The fourth jet airliner crashed into a field near [[Shanksville, Pennsylvania|Shanksville]], [[Pennsylvania]], after some of its passengers and flight crew attempted to retake control of the jet airliners, which the hijackers had redirected toward Washington D.C., to target the [[White House]] or the [[U.S. Capitol]]. None of the flights had any survivors. A total of 2,977 victims and the 19 hijackers perished in the attacks.<ref>{{cite book |title=The Impact of 9/11 on Politics and War: The Day that Changed Everything? |author=Matthew J. Morgan |page=222|date= 4 August 2009 |publisher=Palgrave Macmillan|isbn=978-0-2306-07637}}</ref> Fifteen of the nineteen were citizens of [[Saudi Arabia]], and the others were from the [[United Arab Emirates]] (2), [[Egypt]], and [[Lebanon]].<ref name="cia.gov">{{cite web|url=https://www.cia.gov/news-information/speeches-testimony/2002/DCI_18_June_testimony_new.pdf|title=CIA Document "DCI Testimony Before the Joint Inquiry into Terrorist Attacks Against the United States" |date=June 18, 2002 |website= www.cia.gov/news-information/speeches-testimony/2002/|publisher=}}</ref>

On 13 September, for the first time ever, [[NATO]] invoked [[North Atlantic Treaty#Article 5|Article 5]] of the [[North Atlantic Treaty]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2001/09/13/us/after-attacks-alliance-for-first-time-nato-invokes-joint-defense-pact-with-us.html|title=AFTER THE ATTACKS: THE ALLIANCE; For First Time, NATO Invokes Joint Defense Pact With U.S|first=Suzanne|last=Daley|date=13 September 2001|publisher=|via=NYTimes.com}}</ref> On 18 September 2001, President Bush signed the [[Authorization for Use of Military Force Against Terrorists]] passed by Congress a few days prior.

==U.S. objectives==

[[File:Battlefields in The Global War on Terror.svg|thumb|upright=1.6|

{{legend|#89e885|[[NATO]]}}
{{legend|#85c3e8|[[Trans-Saharan Counterterrorism Initiative|Trans-Sahara initiative]]}}
{{legend|#ea7070|Major military operations ('''[[War in Afghanistan (2001–present)|Afghanistan]] • [[War in Waziristan|Pakistan]] • [[Iraq War|Iraq]] • [[Somali Civil War|Somalia]] • [[Terrorism in Yemen|Yemen]]''')}}
{{legend|#bee885|Other allies involved in major operations}}

[[File:Circle Burgundy Solid.svg|13px]] Major terrorist attacks by al-Qaeda and affiliated groups:
<small>''1. [[1998 United States embassy bombings]] • 2. [[September 11 attacks|11 September 2001 attacks]] • 3. [[2002 Bali bombings|Bali bombings 2002]]• 4. [[2004 Madrid train bombings|Madrid bombings 2004]] • 5. [[2005 London bombings|London bombings 2005]] • 6. [[2008 Mumbai attacks|Mumbai attacks 2008]]''</small>]]

The [[Authorization for Use of Military Force Against Terrorists]] or "AUMF" was made law on 14 September 2001, to authorize the use of United States Armed Forces against those responsible for the attacks on 11 September 2001.
It authorized the President to use all necessary and appropriate force against those nations, organizations, or persons he determines planned, authorized, committed, or aided the terrorist attacks that occurred on 11 September 2001, or harbored such organizations or persons, to prevent any future acts of international terrorism against the United States by such nations, organizations or individuals. Congress declares this is intended to constitute specific statutory authorization within the meaning of section 5(b) of the [[War Powers Resolution]] of 1973.

The [[George W. Bush administration]] defined the following objectives in the War on Terror:<ref name="NatStratCombatTerror">{{cite web|url=https://georgewbush-whitehouse.archives.gov/news/releases/2003/02/20030214-7.html|title=President Bush Releases National Strategy for Combating Terrorism|date=14 February 2003|publisher=|accessdate=14 September 2014}}</ref>

# Defeat terrorists such as [[Osama bin Laden]], [[Abu Musab al-Zarqawi]] and demolish their organizations
# Identify, locate and demolish terrorists along with their organizations
# Deny sponsorship, support and sanctuary to terrorists
## End the [[state sponsorship of terrorism]]
## Establish and maintain an international standard of accountability concerning combating terrorism
## Strengthen and sustain the international effort to combat terrorism
## Work with willing and able states
## Enable weak states
## Persuade reluctant states
## Compel unwilling states
## Interdict and disorder material support for terrorists
## Abolish terrorist sanctuaries and havens
# Diminish the underlying conditions that terrorists seek to exploit
